quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
34,15,"For Sheba {1} there was also a Sign in their dwelling place: {2} the two gardens {3} to the right and to the left.“ Eat of your Lord's provision, and render thanks to Him. Most pleasant is your land and Most Forgiving is your Lord.”",footnotes:1:To understand the continuity of the subject matter one should keep in view the theme as expressed in( Ayats 1-9). There it has been pointed out that the pagans of Arabia regarded the coming of the Hereafter as irrational
34,16,"But they turned away {1} and so We let loose upon them a devastating flood {2} that swept away the dams and replaced their gardens by two others bearing bitter fruits, tamarisks, and a few lote trees. {3}",footnotes:1:That is
34,17,"Thus did We retribute them for their ingratitude. And none do We retribute in this manner except the utterly ungrateful."
34,18,"We placed other prominent towns between them, the towns that We had blessed and had set well-measured stages between them. {1} Move back and forth between them, night and day, in perfect security.",footnotes:1:“Towns which We had blessed”: The lands of Syria and Palestine
34,19,"But they said: “Lord, make the stages of our journeys longer.” {1} They wronged their own selves so We reduced them to bygone tales, and utterly tore them to pieces. {2} Verily there are Signs in this for everyone who is steadfast and thankful. {3}",footnotes:1:They may not have prayed thus in so many words. As a matter of fact
34,20,"Iblis found his estimate of them to be true, and they followed him, except a party of the believers. {1}",footnotes:1:History shows that in ancient times there lived among the Sabaeans a small group of the people
34,21,"Iblis had no authority over them and whatever happened was in order that We might know him who believes in the Hereafter as distinct from him who is in doubt about it. {1} Your Lord is watchful over everything. {2}",footnotes:1:That is
34,22,"(O Prophet), {1} say to those who associate others with Allah in His Divinity: “Call upon those whom you fancied to be deities beside Allah. {2} They own not even the smallest particle, neither in the heavens nor on the earth; nor do they have any share in the ownership of either of them. Nor is any of them even a helper of Allah.",footnotes:1:Until now the mushriks’ wrong notions about the Hereafter have been dealt with. From here the discourse turns to the refutation of shirk itself.|180512:That is
